{"items":[{"title":"Synology is tightening restrictions on third-party NAS hard drives","link":"https://www.theverge.com/news/652364/synology-nas-third-party-hard-drive-restrictions","pubDate":"2025-04-19T21:54:13.000Z","author":"Wes Davis","content":"\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\n<figure>\n\n<img alt=\"\" data-caption=\"\" data-portal-copyright=\"\" data-has-syndication-rights=\"1\" src=\"https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/04/SynologyDS224-Plus.png?quality=90&#038;strip=all&#038;crop=0,0,100,100\" />\n\t<figcaption></figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p class=\"has-text-align-none\">Synology is preparing to roll out new restrictions on third-party hard drives in its future network attached storage (NAS) devices later this year, the company <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2025/04/synology-confirms-need-for-synology-branded-drives-in-newer-plus-series-nas/\">confirmed to <em>Ars Technica</em></a><em>.</em> The changes could make it much harder to use third-party drives in Synology‚Äôs devices for typical use cases, like backing up household computers or as local media servers. The good news is that if you already own a Synology NAS, the company says the change won‚Äôt affect you.</p>\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-none\">Synology says in an EU <a href=\"https://www.synology.com/en-eu/company/news/article/DACH_VL_plus/Synology%20is%20increasingly%20relying%20on%20its%20own%20ecosystem%20for%20upcoming%20Plus%20models\">press release</a> that ‚Äústarting with Plus Series models released in 2025,‚Äù only Synology-branded drives and those the company has certified to meet its specifications will ‚Äúoffer the full range of features and support.‚Äù According to <em>Ars</em>, Synology plans to update its compatibility lists to reflect which third-party drives that it has certified. </p>\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-none\">The new restrictions mean that without Synology-approved drives, you might not be able to do things like pool storage between disks or take advantage of drive lifespan analysis offered by the company‚Äôs software. The change doesn‚Äôt apply to Synology J- and- Value-series devices, and won‚Äôt affect consumer-grade Synology Plus devices that were released in 2024 and earlier. Nor will it affect hard drives that are migrated to this year‚Äôs devices from its existing NAS systems, according to Synology‚Äôs press release.</p>\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-none\">As for why it‚Äôs making this change, a Synology spokesperson told <em>Ars</em>, ‚ÄúExtensive internal testing has shown that drives that follow a rigorous validation process when paired with Synology systems are at less risk of drive failure and ongoing compatibility issues.‚Äù The company says similar things in its press release, writing that the restrictions will ‚Äúreduce compatibility issues and increase system reliability and performance.‚Äù Synology did not immediately respond to <em>The Verge</em>‚Äôs request for comment. </p>\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-none\">Restrictions like this are irritating. To Synology‚Äôs credit, it‚Äôs introducing them in a way that‚Äôs less egregious than something like a printer company <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2023/3/11/23635168/hp-printer-update-brick-third-party-ink-dynamic-security\">blocking third-party ink with a software update</a>. But that doesn‚Äôt fix the fact that owners of its future NAS devices will have fewer choices ‚Äî and therefore fewer chances to save money ‚Äî when it comes to buying the drives to stick into them. </p>\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-none\"></p>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t","contentSnippet":"Synology is preparing to roll out new restrictions on third-party hard drives in its future network attached storage (NAS) devices later this year, the company confirmed to Ars Technica. The changes could make it much harder to use third-party drives in Synology‚Äôs devices for typical use cases, like backing up household computers or as local media servers. The good news is that if you already own a Synology NAS, the company says the change won‚Äôt affect you.\nSynology says in an EU press release that ‚Äústarting with Plus Series models released in 2025,‚Äù only Synology-branded drives and those the company has certified to meet its specifications will ‚Äúoffer the full range of features and support.‚Äù According to Ars, Synology plans to update its compatibility lists to reflect which third-party drives that it has certified. \nThe new restrictions mean that without Synology-approved drives, you might not be able to do things like pool storage between disks or take advantage of drive lifespan analysis offered by the company‚Äôs software. The change doesn‚Äôt apply to Synology J- and- Value-series devices, and won‚Äôt affect consumer-grade Synology Plus devices that were released in 2024 and earlier. Nor will it affect hard drives that are migrated to this year‚Äôs devices from its existing NAS systems, according to Synology‚Äôs press release.\nAs for why it‚Äôs making this change, a Synology spokesperson told Ars, ‚ÄúExtensive internal testing has shown that drives that follow a rigorous validation process when paired with Synology systems are at less risk of drive failure and ongoing compatibility issues.‚Äù The company says similar things in its press release, writing that the restrictions will ‚Äúreduce compatibility issues and increase system reliability and performance.‚Äù Synology did not immediately respond to The Verge‚Äôs request for comment. \nRestrictions like this are irritating. To Synology‚Äôs credit, it‚Äôs introducing them in a way that‚Äôs less egregious than something like a printer company blocking third-party ink with a software update. But that doesn‚Äôt fix the fact that owners of its future NAS devices will have fewer choices ‚Äî and therefore fewer chances to save money ‚Äî when it comes to buying the drives to stick into them.","summary":"Synology is preparing to roll out new restrictions on third-party hard drives in its future network attached storage (NAS) devices later this year, the company confirmed to Ars Technica. The changes could make it much harder to use third-party drives in Synology‚Äôs devices for typical use cases, like backing up household computers or as local [&#8230;]","id":"https://www.theverge.com/?p=652364","isoDate":"2025-04-19T21:54:13.000Z"},{"title":"Over 700 events and protests across the US mark ‚ÄòA National Day of Action‚Äô","link":"https://www.theverge.com/news/652341/nation-day-of-action-50501-protests-50-states","pubDate":"2025-04-19T18:00:52.000Z","author":"Wes Davis","content":"\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\n<figure>\n\n<img alt=\"\" data-caption=\"Protesters in Washington, DC on April 5th.\" data-portal-copyright=\"\" data-has-syndication-rights=\"1\" src=\"https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/04/Handsoff-DC-4.jpg?quality=90&#038;strip=all&#038;crop=0,0,100,100\" />\n\t<figcaption>Protesters in Washington, DC on April 5th.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p class=\"has-text-align-none\">More protests against President Donald Trump are taking place today as part of ‚ÄúA National Day of Action‚Äù <a href=\"https://www.fiftyfifty.one/events\">largely spearheaded</a> by the decentralized 50501 movement. Events are <a href=\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/0/viewer?mid=1NiJprGgrxLL6FBEV0Cg2NtkHlLhc-kA&amp;ll=37.762378683056745,-102.48955066897881&amp;z=5\">scheduled in all 50 states</a>, two weeks after millions of people attended <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/policy/644186/hands-off-washington-dc-protest-musk-trump-doge\">more than 1,300 ‚ÄúHands Off!‚Äù protests</a> across the US and the world. </p>\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-none\">This time, <a href=\"https://events.pol-rev.com/search?contentType=EVENTS&amp;when=april19&amp;eventPage=1\">over 700 rallies</a> and community events are planned<em>.</em> A <a href=\"https://www.fiftyfifty.one/post/april-19-a-national-day-of-acti